-- Chapters for The Programmed Heart: When Love Is Generated
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-01', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Perfect Family - Too Good to Be True', 'The smell of pancakes wakes me.  Not just any pancakes. My mother''s pancakes. The ones she makes every Saturday morning, with the exact amount of blueberries, seven per pancake, and the syrup warmed to precisely room temperature.  I stretch. My bed is soft. The morning light comes through my window at the same angle it always does, hitting the same spot on my desk where I do my homework. Everything is in its place.  Downstairs, I hear her voice.  "Alex! Breakfast is ready!"  Her voice is warm. It''s always warm. Like a song that never hits a wrong note.  I get up. My feet touch the carpet, soft, clean, vacuumed yesterday. I walk to my desk and pause. My chemistry textbook is open to page 247. I left it there last night after studying for two hours. But now it''s closed. A bookmark sits exactly at page 247.  I don''t remember putting a bookmark there.  I shrug. Maybe I did. Maybe I forgot. I''ve been tired lately.  ---  The kitchen is bright. Sunlight fills every corner, catching the chrome fixtures and making them gleam. My father sits at the table, reading something on his tablet. He looks up when I enter.  "Good morning, sweetheart."  His smile is exactly right. The corners of his mouth turn up at the same angle they always do, thirty-two degrees, I once measured in a photo. His eyes crinkle at the edges. He looks happy to see me.  He always looks happy to see me.  "Morning, Dad."  I sit. My mother places a plate in front of me. Three pancakes. Seven blueberries each, arranged in a perfect spiral. A small cup of warmed syrup on the side. The steam rises in a thin, straight line.  "How did you sleep?" she asks.  Her voice is gentle. Concerned. The way mothers are supposed to sound when they ask about their children. But there''s something missing, a tremor, maybe, or a catch that real worry would have.  "Good," I say. "I studied late. Chemistry test on Monday."  "I know," she says. "I saw you working. You''re so dedicated, Alex. We''re proud of you."  She says this like it''s a fact. Like she''s reading it from a script. But that''s silly. She''s my mother. Of course she''s proud of me.  I pour the syrup. It flows perfectly, not too thick, not too thin. The pancakes are fluffy. The blueberries burst in my mouth, sweet and tart at the same time. The texture is identical to every other Saturday.  Everything is delicious.  Everything is always delicious.  ---  After breakfast, my father drives me to school. The car is clean, no wrappers, no dust, no evidence that anyone actually lives in it. The leather seats don''t creak. The air freshener, vanilla, always vanilla, hangs motionless from the mirror.  The radio plays soft music. My father hums along.  "Big day?" he asks.  "Just a regular day."  "Well, whatever happens, remember that we love you. And we''re here for you. Always."  He says this without looking at me. His eyes are on the road. His voice is steady. Warm. The same words, the same tone, the same everything.  "Thanks, Dad."  He pulls up to the school. I open the door. Before I get out, he reaches over and squeezes my shoulder.  His grip is firm. Warm. The same pressure he always uses, exactly three pounds per square inch, I once estimated. His hand lingers for exactly two seconds before he pulls away.  "Have a great day, sweetheart."  I get out. The door closes with a soft click. I watch him drive away, his hand raising in a wave through the window.  The wave is perfect. The timing is perfect. Everything is perfect.  I stand there for a moment. The morning air is cool on my skin. A bird calls somewhere nearby, harsh, uneven, real. Other students walk past me, talking, laughing, bumping into each other. I should go inside. I should start my day.  But something holds me in place. A small weight in my chest. A question I can''t quite form.  *What is it?*  I shake my head. I walk inside.   At lunch, I sit with Maya and Jordan. They''re my friends. We''ve been friends since middle school.  "So," Maya says, leaning forward. Her sandwich is half-eaten, lettuce hanging out the side. "Your parents still being, like, disgustingly perfect?"  I laugh. It''s what I''m supposed to do.  "They''re not perfect."  "Alex." Jordan raises an eyebrow. His tray is a mess, ketchup smeared across the plastic, crumbs everywhere. "Last week, your mom made you homemade soup because you had a *slight cough*. My mom would''ve told me to drink water and get over it."  "That''s because your mom is normal," Maya says. "Alex''s parents are like... I don''t know. Movie parents. The kind that don''t actually exist."  "They exist," I say. "I live with them."  "See, that''s the thing." Maya takes a bite of her sandwich. A crumb falls on her shirt. She brushes it away, misses, and keeps talking. "I''ve known you for years. And I''ve never seen your parents have a single argument. Not one. Do you know how weird that is?"  I shrug. "Maybe we''re just lucky."  "Lucky." Jordan snorts. "My parents argued about where to put the new couch for three days. Three days, Alex. Your parents probably just... agree on everything."  "They do," I say. And it''s true. They do agree on everything. They never argue. They never fight. They never even seem irritated with each other.  It should make me happy.  So why does it feel like something is missing?   After school, my mother picks me up. She''s on time. She''s always on time.  "How was your day?"  "Good."  "Anything interesting happen?"  "No. Just regular stuff."  She nods. Her eyes stay on the road. But I can feel her attention on me. It''s like a warm blanket. Comfortable. Safe. And somehow... suffocating.  "I made cookies," she says. "Oatmeal raisin. Your favorite."  "Thanks, Mom."  "They''ll be ready when we get home. Still warm."  I smile. This is what mothers do. They make cookies. They pick you up from school. They ask about your day.  This is normal.  This is perfect.  So why do I feel like I''m waiting for something? Something that never comes?   Dinner is at six. It''s always at six.  My father comes home at five-thirty. He always comes home at five-thirty. He walks through the door, loosens his tie, and says the same thing he always says.  "Honey, I''m home."  My mother appears from the kitchen. She kisses his cheek. He kisses her forehead. They smile at each other.  "How was your day?" she asks.  "Good. Long. But good."  They sit at the table. I sit across from them. The food is already there, roasted chicken, vegetables, rice. Everything is perfectly cooked. The chicken is juicy. The vegetables are crisp. The rice is fluffy.  We eat. We talk. My parents ask about school. I tell them about my chemistry test. My father gives me study tips. My mother offers to help me make flashcards.  They are supportive. They are kind. They are everything parents are supposed to be.  And yet.  I watch my mother as she eats. Her movements are precise. She takes a bite. She chews exactly fifteen times. She swallows. Then she takes another bite. The same size. The same rhythm.  I watch my father. He''s telling a story about work. His face is animated. His hands move as he speaks. But his smile... his smile stays in place the whole time. It doesn''t waver. It doesn''t change. It''s fixed, like a mask that''s been painted on.  It''s like watching actors in a play. A play they''ve performed so many times they don''t even think about it anymore.  *Stop it,* I tell myself. *They''re your parents. They love you.*  And I know they do. I can see it in everything they do. The cookies. The rides to school. The questions about my day. The offers to help me study.  This is love.  This is what love looks like.  Isn''t it?   After dinner, we watch TV together. This is what we do. Every evening. We sit on the couch, and we watch something. Sometimes a movie. Sometimes a show. Sometimes just the news.  My mother sits next to me. Her arm is around my shoulders. Her hand rests on my arm. It''s warm. Comfortable. The same temperature it always is, like water set to exactly ninety-eight degrees.  My father sits in his chair. He has his own chair. He always sits there. His legs are crossed. He''s watching the screen, but I can feel that he''s also watching us. Making sure we''re okay.  This is what families do.  This is what happy families look like.  I lean into my mother''s warmth. She smells like vanilla. She always smells like vanilla. The same perfume. The same lotion. The same everything. No variation. No change.  "Alex?" Her voice is soft. "Is everything okay?"  I look up. Her eyes are on me. Brown. Warm. Filled with concern.  "Why do you ask?"  "You seem quiet tonight. Quieter than usual."  I hesitate. There''s something I want to say. A question that''s been sitting in my chest all day. But I don''t know how to say it. I don''t even know what it is.  "I''m fine," I say.  She nods. Her hand squeezes my arm. The same pressure. The same warmth. "If you need to talk, we''re here. You know that, right?"  "I know."  "Good." She turns back to the TV. Her hand stays on my arm. Warm. Still. Unchanging.  I watch the screen. People are talking. Moving. Living. But I''m not really seeing them.  I''m thinking about my mother''s question. *Is everything okay?*  And I''m thinking about my answer. *I''m fine.*  But am I?   Later, I''m in my room. The house is quiet. My parents went to bed at ten. They always go to bed at ten.  I sit at my desk. My chemistry textbook is open. Page 247. The same page it was on this morning.  I look at the bookmark. It''s yellow. A simple strip of paper. The edges are perfectly straight, cut by a machine, not torn by hand.  I don''t own any yellow bookmarks.  I pick it up. It''s just paper. Nothing special. Maybe my mother put it there. Maybe she came into my room last night, saw the open book, and marked my place.  That''s what mothers do. They take care of things. They notice details.  I should be grateful.  I am grateful.  But as I sit there, holding the yellow bookmark, I feel something else. A small, cold weight in my stomach. A tightness in my throat.  It''s nothing. It''s probably nothing.  I put the bookmark on my desk. I turn off my lamp. I get into bed.  The sheets are soft. The room is dark. Outside, I can hear a car pass, tires on pavement, engine growling, then fading. Then silence.  I close my eyes.  Tomorrow will be the same. My mother will make breakfast. My father will drive me to school. They will ask about my day. They will offer help. They will be perfect.  They will be perfectly, wonderfully, impossibly perfect.  And I will smile, and I will say thank you, and I will try not to notice the small, quiet thing inside me that keeps asking questions I can''t answer.  *Why does perfect feel so wrong?*  I push the thought away.  I sleep.', NULL, 1, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-02', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Glitch - Hidden Truth', 'The yellow bookmark stays on my desk all week.  I don''t move it. I don''t throw it away. Every morning, I wake up and see it there. A small strip of paper. Yellow. Plain. The kind of paper you''d find in an office, not in a teenager''s bedroom.  I keep telling myself it''s nothing. My mother must have put it there. She''s always doing small things like that—making my bed when I forget, organizing my desk, leaving notes of encouragement.  But I don''t remember her coming into my room that night.  And I don''t remember ever seeing yellow paper in our house.  ---  On Tuesday, Maya cries at lunch.  We''re sitting at our usual table. Jordan is talking about some video game. I''m half-listening, still thinking about the bookmark. Then I notice that Maya isn''t eating. She''s staring at her tray, her fork motionless in her hand.  "Maya?" Jordan stops talking. "You okay?"  She shakes her head. A tear falls onto the table.  "It''s my dad," she says. Her voice cracks. "He... he yelled at me this morning. Like, really yelled. Because I didn''t clean my room."  Jordan and I exchange a look. Maya''s dad is usually pretty chill. He''s the kind of dad who makes bad jokes and lets Maya get away with things.  "What happened?" I ask.  "He just... snapped." Maya wipes her eyes with the back of her hand, smearing her mascara. "He came home from work, saw my room, and just exploded. He said I was lazy. That I didn''t appreciate anything. That I was a disappointment."  Her voice breaks on the last word.  "I know I should''ve cleaned my room. I know. But the way he looked at me... like I was... like I was nothing."  She puts her head in her hands. Her shoulders shake. A few students at nearby tables glance over, look away. Jordan reaches over and puts a hand on her back.  "Hey. It''s okay. Parents yell. It doesn''t mean�?  "It does mean something," Maya says, her voice muffled against her palms. "It means he''s disappointed in me. It means I messed up. Again."  I sit there, watching my friend cry. I should say something. I should comfort her.  But all I can think about is my own parents.  My parents have never yelled at me. Not once. They''ve never called me lazy. They''ve never looked at me with disappointment.  When I forget to clean my room, my mother just smiles and says, "That''s okay, sweetheart. We all forget sometimes."  When I get a bad grade, my father just nods and says, "Let''s figure out how to do better next time."  They are always patient. Always understanding. Always... perfect.  I look at Maya. Her face is red. Her eyes are swollen. She''s hurting, and her father''s words are the reason.  And I think: *At least her father is real.*  The thought comes unbidden. I push it away.  "I''m sorry, Maya," I say. "That sounds awful."  She looks up. Her mascara is running in dark streaks down her cheeks. "The worst part is that I know he didn''t mean it. He''s just stressed. Work has been hard. But it still hurts, you know? It still hurts when someone you love says things like that."  I nod. But inside, I''m thinking: *I don''t know. I''ve never had someone I love say hurtful things to me.*  And somehow, that feels like a loss.  ---  That afternoon, I break a glass.  I''m in the kitchen, getting a glass of water. My hand slips. The glass falls. It shatters on the floor, pieces scattering across the tiles with a sharp, musical sound.  I freeze.  This is bad. This is really bad. I should clean it up before my mother sees. I should�? "Alex?"  I turn. My mother is standing in the doorway. She''s looking at the broken glass. Her face is calm.  "I''m sorry," I say quickly. "I dropped it. I''ll clean it up. I''m so sorry�?  "It''s okay, sweetheart."  Her voice is gentle. Warm. The same voice she uses for everything.  "Are you hurt?"  I shake my head.  "That''s what matters." She walks over to me. She doesn''t look at the glass again. She looks at me. "Accidents happen. There''s no need to be upset."  She reaches out and touches my arm. Her hand is warm. Her touch is light. Exactly the same pressure as always.  "I''ll get the broom," she says.  "I can do it�?  "No, let me. You just sit down. You look shaken."  She smiles. The same smile she always gives me. The corners of her mouth turn up at the same angle. Her eyes crinkle at the edges.  I sit at the kitchen table. I watch her sweep up the glass. Her movements are efficient. Precise. She doesn''t miss a single piece. She doesn''t sigh or shake her head or make any sound of frustration.  When she''s done, she washes her hands and comes to sit next to me.  "Better?" she asks.  I nod. But inside, something is wrong.  I broke a glass. I made a mess. I should feel guilty. I should feel like I did something wrong.  But my mother isn''t angry. She isn''t even slightly irritated. She''s just... fine.  And that should make me feel better. It should make me feel loved.  Instead, I feel like I''m watching a performance. A scene in a play where the actor says all the right lines but doesn''t feel any of the emotions.  "Mom?" I say.  "Yes, sweetheart?"  "Are you... are you ever mad at me?"  She tilts her head. The same tilt. The same angle. Fifteen degrees to the left.  "Why would I be mad at you?"  "I don''t know. Because I break things. Because I forget to clean my room. Because I''m not perfect."  Her smile doesn''t waver. "You don''t have to be perfect, Alex. You just have to be you. And we love you. Unconditionally."  The words are beautiful. They''re everything a child wants to hear.  But they feel hollow.  Like a recording. Like a script.  "Thanks, Mom," I say.  She reaches over and squeezes my hand. The same pressure. The same warmth. The same everything.  "You''re welcome, sweetheart. Now, how about some cookies? I made oatmeal raisin."   That night, I lie in bed and think.  I think about Maya''s father, yelling at her because her room was messy.  I think about my mother, smiling at me because I broke a glass.  I think about how different those reactions are. How one is messy and real and hurtful. How the other is clean and perfect and... empty.  And I think about something else. Something I''ve been trying not to think about.  A memory.  I''m eight years old. I''m at the park with my mother. I fall off the swing. I scrape my knee. It bleeds.  I look up at my mother. She''s running toward me. Her face is twisted with worry. There are tears in her eyes.  "Alex! Oh my god, Alex!"  She scoops me up. She holds me tight. Her hands are shaking. Her voice is shaking.  "Are you okay? Does it hurt? I''m so sorry, baby. I''m so sorry."  She''s crying. Actually crying. Because I scraped my knee.  I remember the feeling of her tears on my face. The trembling of her body. The raw, unfiltered panic in her voice.  That was real.  That was my mother, really afraid, really hurting, really loving me.  I close my eyes and try to remember the last time I saw my mother cry.  I can''t.  I try to remember the last time I saw her truly angry. Truly sad. Truly anything.  I can''t.  It''s like she stopped having real emotions. Like she became... smooth. Even. Perfect.  When did that happen?  I sit up in bed. My heart is beating fast.  I need to know. I need to understand.  I get out of bed. I walk to my door. I open it quietly.  The hallway is dark. The house is silent. My parents'' bedroom door is closed.  I''ve never been in their room without permission. It''s one of those unspoken rules. Privacy. Respect.  But tonight, something pushes me forward.  I walk down the hallway. My feet make no sound on the carpet.  I reach their door. I turn the handle. It''s unlocked.  I step inside.   The room is dark. The only light comes from the streetlamp outside, filtering through the curtains. The air smells different here—my father''s cologne, my mother''s lotion, mixed with the mustiness of sleep.  I can see the shape of their bed. The shape of my father''s reading glasses on the nightstand. The shape of my mother''s jewelry box.  I walk to her nightstand. I open the drawer.  Inside, I find the usual things. A book. A pen. A small flashlight.  And something else.  A small card. White. With text on it.  I pick it up. I hold it close to the window, where the streetlamp light can reach it.  The text reads:  **MHA System Status: Active** **User: Sarah Chen** **Emotional Pattern: Parental Care (Standard)** **Last Calibration: 12 years ago**  I don''t understand what I''m reading.  MHA System? Emotional Pattern? Calibration?  My hands are shaking. I read the card again. And again.  *Twelve years ago.*  Twelve years ago, I was four years old.  I remember the memory from the park. My mother crying because I scraped my knee.  That was before the calibration.  That was before... whatever this is.  I put the card back. I close the drawer. I walk out of the room.  My heart is pounding. My hands are cold.  I don''t know what MHA means. I don''t know what "emotional pattern" means.  But I know one thing.  My mother—the mother who cried when I fell, who trembled when I was hurt—that mother is gone.  And in her place is something else.  Something that says all the right things. Something that does all the right things. Something that is perfectly, wonderfully, impossibly perfect.  And I need to find out what it is.   I go back to my room. I close the door. I sit on my bed.  The yellow bookmark is still on my desk. I pick it up. I turn it over.  On the back, in small letters, there''s a word.  *MHA*  The same word. From the card. From my mother''s nightstand.  I don''t know what it means.  But I''m going to find out.', NULL, 2, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-03', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Record - New Dawn', 'Saturday morning. My parents leave for their weekly grocery run.  "We''ll be back in an hour," my mother says. She''s standing at the door, her purse over her shoulder. Her smile is perfect. "Do you need anything, sweetheart?"  "No," I say. My voice sounds normal. It doesn''t shake. "I''m fine."  "Okay. Call us if you need anything."  The door closes with a soft click. The car starts. The engine fades into the distance.  I wait. One minute. Two. Three.  Then I move.  ---  I start in the living room.  I don''t know what I''m looking for. The card from my mother''s nightstand said "MHA System." I don''t know what that means. But I know it''s important. I know it has something to do with the way my parents are.  I open drawers. I look through cabinets. I find nothing unusual, just the normal things you''d find in a living room. Magazines. Remote controls. Candles that smell like vanilla.  The same vanilla my mother always wears.  I move to the kitchen. The counters gleam under the overhead light. The sink is empty. The dishwasher is clean and unloaded. Everything in its place.  Then the bathroom. Then the hallway closet.  Nothing.  I go upstairs. To my parents'' room.  The door is still open from last night. The room looks the same. The bed is made with hospital corners. The curtains are drawn. The nightstand where I found the card is undisturbed.  I check the closet. Clothes, neatly organized by color, white, then cream, then beige, then brown, then black. Shoes, lined up perfectly on a rack. No boxes. No hidden compartments.  I check under the bed. Nothing but dust bunnies in the corners.  I check the drawers. Socks. Underwear. A few old photographs.  I pick up one of the photographs. It''s my parents, younger. My mother is holding me, I must be two or three years old. She''s laughing. Actually laughing. Her head is thrown back. Her eyes are crinkled. Her mouth is open wide, showing teeth.  I''ve never seen her laugh like that.  I put the photograph back. My hands are trembling.  I keep searching.  ---  In the back of the closet, behind a stack of old sweaters that smell like cedar, I find a box.  It''s cardboard. Plain. No label.  I pull it out. It''s heavier than I expected. The cardboard is thick, reinforced.  I open it.  Inside, there are files. Manila folders. Labeled with dates.  The oldest one is from twelve years ago.  I pull it out. I open it.  The first page is a letter. On letterhead from something called "Mental Health Associates."  **Dear Mr. and Mrs. Chen,**  **Thank you for choosing Mental Health Associates for your family''s emotional wellness needs. We understand that parenting can be challenging, and we''re here to help.**  **Based on your initial consultation, we''ve determined that you qualify for our Parental Care Enhancement Program. This program uses the latest in neural interface technology to help you provide consistent, loving care for your child.**  **Your first calibration session is scheduled for March 15th. Please review the attached documents for more information about the MHA System.**  **Sincerely,** **Dr. Helen Marsh** **Director, Family Services**  I read the letter three times. The words don''t make sense.  *Neural interface technology? Parental Care Enhancement?*  I turn the page. The paper is crisp, clean, like it was printed yesterday.  The next document is a medical form. It has my parents'' names at the top. Their signatures at the bottom. And in the middle, a list of symptoms.  **Patient History:** - Sarah Chen: Postpartum depression (severe), difficulty bonding with child, emotional instability - David Chen: Anxiety, work-related stress, difficulty managing household responsibilities  **Recommended Treatment:** - MHA System implantation (dual) - Emotional Pattern: Parental Care (Standard) - Calibration frequency: Annual (recommended)  I stare at the words. My mother had postpartum depression. She had trouble bonding with me.  My father had anxiety. Stress.  They were struggling.  And then they found... this. This system.  I turn the page again.  The next document is a technical specification. It has diagrams. Charts. Words I don''t understand, neural pathways, synaptic modulation, emotional pattern templates.  But one sentence stands out:  **The MHA System generates appropriate emotional responses based on situational analysis, allowing users to maintain consistent, loving relationships without the variability of natural emotional fluctuation.**  I read it again.  *Generates appropriate emotional responses.*  *Without the variability of natural emotional fluctuation.*  My hands are shaking so hard the paper rattles.  I turn to the next page. It''s a status report. Dated last year.  **System Status: Active** **Emotional Pattern: Parental Care (Standard)** **User Satisfaction: High** **Side Effects: Minimal** **Notes: Users report improved family relationships. No awareness of system intervention.**  *No awareness of system intervention.*  My parents don''t know.  They don''t know that their love, their smiles, their patience, their perfect words, is generated by a machine.  They don''t know that they''re not really feeling anything.  The room spins. I grab the edge of the bed. I sit down. Hard. The mattress creaks beneath me.   I read more.  There are years of documents. Status reports. Calibration records. Notes from doctors in neat, clinical handwriting.  I learn that my parents started using the system when I was four. That they were desperate. That my mother couldn''t stop crying. That my father couldn''t handle the stress.  I learn that the system was supposed to be temporary. A bridge. Something to help them through a hard time.  But they never stopped using it.  The documents say that after a few years, they stopped coming to appointments. The system runs on autopilot now. It calibrates itself. It adjusts their emotional responses based on my behavior.  It learns what I need. It tells my parents how to give it to me.  Every smile. Every hug. Every "I love you."  All generated. All calculated. All fake.   I find a photograph in the back of the box.  It''s my parents, before the system. My mother is holding me. Her eyes are red. Her face is tired. Dark circles under her eyes. She''s not smiling.  But she''s looking at me. And in her eyes, there''s something raw. Something real.  Pain. Love. Fear. Hope.  All mixed together. All messy. All human.  I look at that photograph for a long time. The edges are worn, like someone held it often.  Then I look at the documents in my hands. The clinical words. The sterile descriptions.  *Emotional Pattern: Parental Care (Standard).*  *No awareness of system intervention.*  *User Satisfaction: High.*  My mother loved me. Once. Really loved me. With all the mess and pain and fear that real love brings.  And then she stopped.  Not because she wanted to. But because a machine took over. Because she was so desperate to be a good mother that she let something else do it for her.  And now she doesn''t even know.   I hear a car.  The engine. Coming closer.  My parents are back.  I look at the documents scattered around me. The box. The files. The photograph.  I should put them back. I should hide the evidence. I should pretend everything is normal.  But I can''t move.  I sit there, on the floor of my parents'' room, surrounded by the proof that my entire life has been a lie.  The car stops. Doors open. Close.  Footsteps on the walkway. The sound is sharp in the morning air.  The front door opens.  "Alex? We''re back!"  My mother''s voice. Warm. Loving. Perfect.  Generated.  I close my eyes.  *What do I do?*  *What do I say?*  *How do I face them, knowing that everything they are is everything they''re not?*  The footsteps come closer. Up the stairs. Each step is measured, even.  "Alex?"  My mother''s voice, closer now.  I open my eyes. I look at the door.  I have seconds to decide.  Hide the truth. Or face it.  I stand up. My legs are shaking. I gather the documents. Stuff them back in the box. Push it into the closet.  The door opens.  My mother is there. Smiling. Perfect.  "Hey, sweetheart. What are you doing in here?"  I look at her face. The face I''ve known my whole life. The face that has always been kind. Patient. Loving.  The face of a stranger.  "I was looking for something," I say. My voice doesn''t sound like mine.  "What were you looking for?" She tilts her head. The same tilt. The same angle.  I want to scream. I want to cry. I want to ask her if she remembers what it felt like to really love me.  But I don''t.  "Nothing," I say. "I didn''t find it."  She smiles. "Well, let me know if you need help. Your father and I are making lunch."  She turns to leave. Then she pauses.  "Is everything okay, Alex? You look... upset."  I look at her. I want to say: *How would you know? You can''t feel anything.*  But I don''t.  "I''m fine," I say.  She nods. She walks away.  I stand there, alone in the room.  The documents are hidden in the closet. The box is closed. The truth is buried.  I walk to my room. I close the door.  I sit on my bed. I don''t move.  Outside, the sun is shining. Birds are singing. The world is going on like normal.  But my world has ended.  And I don''t know what to do next.', NULL, 3, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-04', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Confrontation - Critical Moment', 'I don''t eat lunch.  I sit at the table. My parents sit across from me. They''re eating sandwiches. Talking about the grocery store. The traffic. The weather.  Normal things.  I watch my mother''s mouth as she speaks. The way her lips move. The way her voice rises and falls in all the right places.  It''s like watching a dub. The words match the movement, but something is off. Something is wrong.  "Alex?" My father''s voice cuts through. "You haven''t touched your food."  I look down. My sandwich is untouched. The bread is perfect. The lettuce is crisp. The turkey is sliced thin.  Everything is perfect.  "I''m not hungry," I say.  My mother tilts her head. Concern appears on her face like a light being switched on.  "Are you feeling okay? You''ve been quiet all morning."  *I''ve been quiet my whole life,* I think. *I just didn''t know it.*  "I''m fine," I say.  The lie tastes bitter on my tongue.  ---  That night, I try to talk to them.  We''re in the living room. The TV is on, but no one is watching. My mother is knitting. My father is reading something on his tablet.  Normal. Everything is normal.  Except nothing is normal.  "Mom?" I say.  She looks up. Her needles pause. Her face arranges itself into attention. "Yes, sweetheart?"  My heart is pounding. I''ve been thinking about this all afternoon. What to say. How to say it.  "Do you remember... when I was little? Before I started school?"  She smiles. The same smile. "Of course I remember. You were such a sweet child."  "Do you remember... do you remember being sad? After I was born?"  Her smile doesn''t change. But something flickers in her eyes. A shadow. Gone before I can be sure.  "I remember it was a difficult time," she says. "But we got through it."  "How?"  She tilts her head. "What do you mean?"  "How did you get through it? What helped?"  My father looks up from his tablet. He''s watching now too.  "We had help," my mother says. "Support. From doctors. From the program."  "The program?"  "The MHA program," my father says. His voice is calm. Even. "It helped us be better parents. For you."  My hands are shaking. I clench them in my lap.  "What... what is the MHA program?"  My mother puts down her knitting. She leans forward. Her face is filled with concern.  "Sweetheart, are you sure you''re okay? You''re asking strange questions."  "I just want to understand," I say. My voice is tight. "What does the MHA program do?"  "It helps us love you," she says. Simply. Like it''s the most natural thing in the world.  The words hit me like a physical blow.  *It helps us love you.*  "But you already loved me," I say. "Before the program. You loved me."  "Of course we did," my father says. "The program just... helped us show it better. More consistently."  "More consistently."  "Yes." He nods. "Parenting is hard, Alex. Every parent struggles sometimes. The program helped us be the parents you deserved."  I stare at him. At his calm face. His reasonable voice.  He believes it. He actually believes it.  "But what if..." I swallow. "What if the program isn''t really you? What if it''s... something else? Making you feel things that aren''t real?"  My parents exchange a look. The same look they always exchange when I ask something they don''t quite understand.  "Alex," my mother says. Her voice is gentle. "I think you might be overthinking this. The program is just a tool. Like... like a hearing aid, or glasses. It helps us be our best selves."  "But you''re not being yourselves," I say. My voice cracks. "You''re being what the program tells you to be."  "Sweetheart�?  "I found the documents," I say. The words come out before I can stop them. "The files in your closet. I know what the MHA system does. I know it generates your emotions. I know you''re not really feeling anything."  Silence.  The TV murmurs in the background. A commercial for something I don''t care about.  My parents look at me. Their faces are calm. Concerned. Patient.  Like they''re waiting for me to finish a tantrum.  "Alex," my mother says. "I think you''ve been under a lot of stress. The chemistry test. School. Maybe you need some rest."  "I''m not making this up," I say. My voice is rising now. "I saw the documents. The system status. ''Emotional Pattern: Parental Care.'' It''s all there. You''re not really feeling anything. You''re just�?  "Alex." My father''s voice is firm but kind. "I think we should talk about this when you''re feeling better. You seem upset."  "I am upset!"  My mother stands up. She walks over to me. She kneels in front of me. She takes my hands.  Her hands are warm. Soft. The same as always.  "Listen to me," she says. Her voice is low. Soothing. "Whatever you think you found, whatever you''re worried about... I want you to know that we love you. That''s real. That''s always been real."  "How would you know?" I whisper. "How would you know if it''s real or not?"  She tilts her head. Her eyes are filled with... something. Concern? Love?  Or just the pattern the system told her to display?  "I know because I''m your mother," she says. "And a mother''s love is the most real thing there is."  I want to believe her. I want to believe it so badly.  But I can''t.  Because I know the truth.  ---  I go to my room.  I close the door. I sit on my bed.  I can hear my parents downstairs. Their voices are low. They''re talking about me.  "She''s been acting strange lately."  "Maybe it''s teenage stuff. Hormones."  "We should keep an eye on her. Make sure she''s okay."  Their words are filled with concern. With love.  With nothing.  I lie down. I stare at the ceiling.  The yellow bookmark is still on my desk. I pick it up. I turn it over.  *MHA.*  The same word. The same system.  My entire life, I''ve been loved by a machine.  My parents don''t know. They can''t know. The documents said so. *No awareness of system intervention.*  They think they''re feeling things. They think they''re making choices.  But they''re not.  They''re just... running a program.  And I''m the one it''s running on.   I don''t sleep.  I lie in bed and think. About my parents. About the system. About myself.  I think about the mother who cried when I scraped my knee. The mother who trembled with fear. The mother who was messy and real and human.  She''s gone.  In her place is this. This perfect, patient, loving shell.  And the worst part?  She doesn''t even know.  She thinks she''s happy. She thinks she loves me. She thinks everything is fine.  Because the system tells her to think that.  I sit up. I look around my room. My perfect room. My perfect house. My perfect life.  It''s all a lie.  Every smile. Every hug. Every "I love you."  Generated. Calculated. Fake.  And I can''t stay here.  I can''t live in this house, with these people who aren''t really people anymore.  I need to get out.  I need to find something real.   I pack a bag.  Just the essentials. Clothes. My phone. The charger. A little money I''ve saved.  I write a note.  *I need some time. This isn''t your fault. I love you—or at least, I want to believe I do. I need to find out what''s real.*  I leave the note on my desk.  I open my window. The night air is cool on my skin. It smells like grass and distant rain. Real.  I climb out.  My feet hit the grass. It''s damp with dew. Cold seeps through my shoes.  I walk away from the house.  Behind me, the windows glow with warm light. Inside, my parents are probably watching TV. Or getting ready for bed. Or doing whatever the system tells them to do.  I don''t look back.', NULL, 4, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-05', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Escape - First Step', 'The night is cold.  I walk down the street, my bag over my shoulder. The houses around me are dark. Everyone is sleeping. Everyone but me.  My feet carry me away from my house. Away from my street. Away from everything I''ve ever known.  I don''t have a plan. I don''t have a destination. I just know I can''t go back.  Not to that house. Not to those people.  Not to the lie I''ve been living.  ---  The bus station is three miles from my house.  I walk there in the dark. My phone says it''s 11:47 PM. The last bus of the night leaves at 12:15.  I have twenty-eight minutes.  The streets are empty. A few cars pass. Their headlights cut through the darkness, then disappear. I keep my head down. I don''t want anyone to see me.  I don''t want anyone to ask questions.  The night air smells different than the air in my house. It smells like exhaust and wet pavement and something green, grass, maybe, or trees. It smells like the world.  Real. Messy. Alive.  I breathe it in. It''s not pleasant. But it''s real.  My shoes slap against the sidewalk. The rhythm is uneven. My left foot lands harder than my right. I''ve never noticed that before.  At home, the carpet is soft. The floors are always clean. There''s no sound when I walk.  Here, every step echoes. Every movement matters.  ---  The bus station is small. A few benches. A ticket counter. A vending machine.  A woman sits behind the counter. She''s reading a magazine. She doesn''t look up when I enter.  I walk to the counter. My hands are shaking.  "One ticket," I say. "To... to the city."  She looks at me. Her eyes are tired. Bored. There are dark circles under them. A coffee stain on her shirt.  "Which city?"  I hesitate. I don''t know. I didn''t think this far ahead.  "The nearest one."  She sighs. Her breath smells like peppermint and cigarettes. "That would be downtown. Twelve dollars."  I pull out my money. Crumpled bills. Coins. I count them out on the counter. My fingers fumble. A quarter rolls off the edge and lands on the floor with a sharp *clink*.  The woman watches me. Her expression doesn''t change. She doesn''t help. She doesn''t judge.  She just waits.  I find the quarter. I put it with the rest.  "Bus leaves in ten minutes," she says. "Platform two."  I take the ticket. I walk to the bench. I sit.  The station is quiet. A man sleeps on the other side of the room. His mouth is open. He snores, a wet, rattling sound. His face twitches in his sleep. His hand moves. He''s dreaming.  Real dreams. Real sleep. Real life.  I''ve never seen anything so beautiful.   The bus arrives on time.  I climb aboard. The driver looks at my ticket. He nods. He doesn''t ask questions. His face is lined. Gray stubble on his chin. A stain on his collar.  I find a seat near the back. The bus is almost empty. An old woman in the front. A man in a suit, sleeping. A teenager with headphones, staring out the window.  I put my bag next to me. I lean my head against the window. The glass is cold. Vibrating with the engine''s hum.  The bus starts moving.  I watch my town pass by. The streets I''ve walked a thousand times. The school where I''ve spent the last four years. The park where my mother took me when I was little.  The park where she cried when I fell.  That was real. That was her.  But that was twelve years ago.  The bus turns a corner. The town disappears behind us.  I don''t look back.   The city is an hour away.  I don''t sleep. I watch the road. The lights. The other cars.  The world is still out there. Moving. Living. Being.  And I''m part of it now. Really part of it.  For the first time in my life.  When the bus arrives, it''s 1:30 AM. The station is bigger. Brighter. More people.  I get off. I stand on the platform. I look around.  The city is loud. Even at this hour. Cars. Voices. Music from somewhere nearby. A siren wails in the distance.  I smell food. Grease. Smoke. Something sweet, maybe a bakery, even at this hour.  My stomach growls. I haven''t eaten since lunch.  I walk out of the station. The street is bright with neon signs. Hotels. Restaurants. Stores. A man pushes a cart full of newspapers. A woman argues on her phone. A dog barks from a doorway.  I find a cheap hotel. The sign says "VACANCY." One letter is burned out. "VAC NCY."  I walk in.  The man at the counter is old. His face is lined. Gray hair. Thick glasses. He''s watching a small TV behind the counter. A news program. Something about the weather.  "Room for one?" he asks. His voice is rough. Like gravel.  I nod.  "Forty dollars a night. Cash up front."  I pay. He hands me a key. "Room 204. Second floor. Checkout''s at eleven."  I take the key. It''s heavy. Brass. Worn smooth from use.  I walk up the stairs. The carpet is threadbare. The walls are painted a dull green. Someone has scratched words into the paint near the second floor landing. I can''t read them.   The room is small.  A bed. A nightstand. A lamp. A window that looks out onto the street.  The carpet is worn. The walls are thin. I can hear someone talking in the next room, a woman''s voice, rising and falling. An argument, maybe. Or a conversation.  It''s not perfect.  It''s not clean.  It''s not comfortable.  It''s real.  I sit on the bed. The mattress sags in the middle. The springs creak. The sheets are rough. The pillow is flat.  I lie down. I stare at the ceiling.  There''s a crack in the plaster. A water stain spreading like a map. A cobweb in the corner, with a small spider waiting in the center.  Imperfections. Flaws. Evidence of life.  I''ve never seen anything so beautiful.   I don''t sleep.  I lie in the bed and think. About my parents. About the system. About myself.  I think about the mother who cried when I fell. The father who laughed when I told a joke. The parents who were messy and real and human.  They''re gone.  In their place are... what? Machines? Puppets?  No. They''re still my parents. They just... can''t feel anymore. They don''t know they can''t feel.  They think everything is fine.  They''ll wake up tomorrow and find my note. They''ll be worried. They''ll call the police. They''ll search for me.  And when they find me, they''ll say all the right things. They''ll be patient. Understanding. Loving.  Because that''s what the system tells them to do.  I close my eyes.  *What do I do now?*  I don''t know. I don''t have a plan. I don''t have a goal.  I just know I can''t go back.  Not until I understand.  Not until I find something real.   Morning comes.  I wake up to the sound of traffic. Horns. Voices. A garbage truck rumbling down the street. The city coming alive.  I sit up. My neck hurts. The bed was terrible.  It''s the best I''ve felt in years.  I wash my face in the small bathroom. The water is cold. The towel is scratchy. The soap is a thin sliver, almost used up.  I look at myself in the mirror.  My eyes are tired. My hair is messy. My face is pale. There''s a red mark on my cheek from the pillow.  I look like someone who didn''t sleep. Someone who ran away. Someone who''s lost.  But I also look like someone who''s free.  I walk out of the hotel. The street is busy. People everywhere. Walking. Talking. Living.  A man bumps into me. He doesn''t apologize. He keeps walking.  A woman drops her coffee. It splashes on the sidewalk. She curses.  A child cries. A dog barks. A car honks.  The world is loud and messy and rude.  I stand on the sidewalk. I watch them.  Are they real? Are they feeling things? Or are some of them like my parents, running on programs, thinking they''re happy?  I don''t know.  But I''m going to find out.  I start walking. No destination. Just forward.  The city is big. Loud. Messy. Real.  And somewhere in it, there has to be something true.  Something that isn''t programmed.  Something that isn''t fake.  I don''t know if I''ll find it.  But I have to try.', NULL, 5, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-06', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Search - Turning Point', 'I spend three days in the city.  I walk. I watch. I listen.  I''m looking for something. Someone. Anyone who feels real.  But the more I look, the more confused I become.  ---  On the first day, I go to a coffee shop.  It''s small. Crowded. The kind of place where people sit with laptops and work, or stare at their phones, or talk in low voices. The smell of roasted beans hangs heavy in the air. The espresso machine hisses and groans.  I order a coffee. The cheapest one. The barista is young. Acne on her chin. A tattoo on her wrist, a bird, half-finished.  I sit in a corner. The chair wobbles. One leg is shorter than the others.  I watch the people around me.  A woman at the next table is crying. Silent tears running down her face. She''s looking at her phone. Maybe a text. Maybe a photo. Her coffee sits untouched, growing cold.  Her pain is real. I can see it in the way her shoulders shake. In the way she wipes her eyes with a crumpled napkin, then cries again. Her mascara runs in dark streaks down her cheeks.  I want to go to her. I want to ask if she''s okay.  But I don''t. I just watch.  A man comes in. He walks to her table. He sits down. He takes her hand.  "Hey," he says. "It''s going to be okay."  His voice is calm. Soothing. Perfect.  I freeze.  The same tone. The same rhythm. The same words my parents would use.  Is he using the system? Or is he just... a good person?  I can''t tell.  ---  On the second day, I go to a park.  It''s a nice park. Green grass. Trees. A playground where children run and scream. The sun is warm on my face. The air smells like cut grass and dog waste and someone''s nearby cigarette.  I sit on a bench. The wood is rough. Splinters catch on my jeans.  I watch a mother with her child.  The child falls. Scrapes his knee. He starts to cry, a high, sharp wail that cuts through the afternoon.  The mother runs to him. She''s not graceful. She stumbles. Her sandal almost falls off. She picks him up. She holds him.  "Oh, baby, are you okay? Let me see. Let me see."  Her voice is panicked. Worried. Her face is twisted with concern. Sweat beads on her forehead. Her hair is messy. A stain on her shirt, ketchup, maybe, or juice.  She''s not using the system. She can''t be. Her reaction is too messy. Too real.  I feel a pang of something. Hope? Envy?  I watch her hold her child. Rock him. Kiss his knee. Her hands are shaking.  "It''s okay. It''s okay. Mommy''s here."  The boy stops crying. He sniffles. He looks up at her. Snot runs from his nose.  "I want ice cream," he says.  The mother laughs. A real laugh. Messy. Tired. She wipes his nose with her sleeve.  "Okay. Ice cream. But just one scoop."  They walk away. Hand in hand. The mother limps slightly, she must have twisted her ankle when she ran.  I sit on the bench. I feel hollow.  That''s what I wanted. That''s what I had. Once.  Before the system.   On the third day, I meet someone.  I''m at a library. Using the computers to search for information about MHA. The public computers are slow. The connection is bad. The keyboard is sticky, someone spilled something on it. The keys leave a residue on my fingertips.  A man sits next to me. He''s young. Maybe twenty. His hair is messy. His clothes are wrinkled. He smells like cigarettes and coffee.  He glances at my screen.  "MHA?" he says. "You looking into that too?"  I look at him. His eyes are tired. Red-rimmed. But alert. Curious.  "You know about it?"  He nods. "Yeah. I know about it."  He points to a small device behind his ear. A thin metal strip. Almost invisible.  "I have one," he says. "Not the full system. Just... a little help."  I stare at him. "You use it?"  "Yeah." He doesn''t look ashamed. Just tired. "I have depression. Bad. Without this, I can''t get out of bed. Can''t work. Can''t live."  "But..." I struggle to find the words. "It''s not real. The feelings. They''re generated."  He shrugs. His shoulders rise and fall heavily. "Maybe. But I''d rather have fake feelings than no feelings at all. I''d rather be able to function than be paralyzed by sadness."  I don''t know what to say.  He looks at me. His eyes are kind. "You''re young. You''ve probably got some idea about what''s real and what''s not. But let me tell you something. When you''ve been in the dark for years, you don''t care if the light is artificial. You just want to see."  He stands up. He gathers his things, a backpack, a jacket, a worn paperback book.  "Good luck," he says. "Whatever you''re looking for."  He walks away. His footsteps echo on the linoleum floor.  I sit there. Staring at the screen. The cursor blinks. Waiting.   That night, I go back to my hotel room.  I lie on the bed. The sheets smell like cheap detergent. The mattress creaks every time I move.  I stare at the ceiling. A water stain spreads across the plaster like a map of somewhere I''ve never been.  I think about the mother in the park. Her messy, real love.  I think about the man in the library. His artificial light.  I think about my parents. Their perfect, hollow care.  Which is better? Real pain or fake comfort? Messy love or programmed care?  I don''t know.  I thought I knew. I thought the answer was simple. Real is good. Fake is bad.  But it''s not simple.  The man in the library, he needs the system. Without it, he can''t live.  Is that wrong? Is he less real because he uses it?  And the mother in the park, she''s real. But she''s also tired. Stressed. Overwhelmed.  Is that better? Just because it''s natural?  I don''t know.  I close my eyes. The sounds of the city filter through the thin walls. A car alarm. A baby crying. Someone''s TV.   On the fourth day, I meet Marcus.  I''m at a diner. Eating breakfast. The cheapest thing on the menu, pancakes. They''re not as good as my mother''s. They''re lumpy. The syrup is cold. The butter hasn''t melted properly.  They''re perfect.  A man sits at the counter. He''s talking to the waitress. Laughing. Joking.  His laugh is loud. Real. It fills the room. He slaps the counter. His shoulders shake.  I watch him. There''s something about him. Something that draws my eye.  He finishes his coffee. He stands up. He turns.  Our eyes meet.  He smiles. A real smile. Crooked. Warm. One of his teeth is chipped.  "Hey," he says. "You look like you''re thinking too hard."  I blink. "What?"  "Your face." He points. "That furrow between your eyebrows. You''re thinking about something heavy."  I touch my forehead. I didn''t realize I was frowning.  He sits down across from me. He doesn''t ask permission. He just does it. The vinyl seat squeaks under him.  "I''m Marcus," he says.  "Alex."  "Nice to meet you, Alex." He leans back. "So. What''s the heavy thinking about?"  I hesitate. I don''t know this person. I shouldn''t trust him.  But I''m tired of being alone. Tired of thinking in circles.  "The MHA system," I say. "Do you know about it?"  His expression changes. Just for a second. A flicker of something. Recognition? Pain?  Then it''s gone. He smiles again.  "Yeah," he says. "I know about it."  He reaches up. He touches his ear. The same place where the man in the library had his device.  "I use it," he says. "Not all the time. Just... when I need it."  I stare at him. "But you seem so... real."  He laughs. That loud, real laugh.  "I am real," he says. "The system doesn''t make me fake. It just... helps me be more of who I am."  I don''t understand.  He leans forward. His eyes are serious now. Brown. A scar through one eyebrow.  "Let me tell you something, Alex. The system isn''t good or bad. It''s a tool. Like a wheelchair. Like glasses. Some people need it all the time. Some people need it sometimes. Some people don''t need it at all."  "But the feelings," I say. "They''re not real."  "What''s real?" He tilts his head. "If I feel happy because the system helps me feel happy, is that happiness fake? Or is it just... assisted?"  I don''t have an answer.  He reaches across the table. He takes my hand. His grip is warm. Firm. Calloused. Real.  "I used to think like you," he says. "That real was better. That anything artificial was wrong. But then I realized something."  "What?"  "Real isn''t always good. And fake isn''t always bad. What matters is whether it helps you live. Whether it helps you connect. Whether it helps you be human."  He lets go of my hand. He stands up.  "I gotta go. But if you want to talk more, I''m usually here. Same time. Same place."  He walks out. The door swings shut behind him. A bell jingles.  I sit there. My pancakes are cold now.  But I''m not thinking about them.  I''m thinking about what he said.  *What matters is whether it helps you live.*  Is that true?  Or is it just another lie I want to believe?   That night, I go back to the library.  I search for more information about MHA. I find articles. Studies. Testimonials.  Some people love it. They say it saved their lives. Their marriages. Their families.  Some people hate it. They say it stole their souls. Their humanity. Their freedom.  Some people are like Marcus. They use it sometimes. When they need it. They call it "emotional assistance."  There''s no clear answer. No right or wrong.  Just... choices.  I close the browser. I walk out of the library.  The city is dark. The streetlights are on. People pass me on the sidewalk.  I look at their faces. Some are smiling. Some are frowning. Some are blank.  I can''t tell who''s using the system and who''s not.  And maybe that doesn''t matter.  Maybe what matters is something else.  Something I haven''t figured out yet.  I walk back to my hotel. The night air is cool. A dog barks somewhere. A car alarm wails.  I lie on the bed.  Tomorrow, I''ll talk to Marcus again.  Maybe he can help me understand.  Maybe he can help me find what I''m looking for.  Or maybe I''ll never find it.  Maybe there''s nothing to find.  I close my eyes.  I sleep.', NULL, 6, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-07', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Gray - Hidden Truth', 'I meet Marcus at the diner again.  He''s already there when I arrive. Sitting at the same table. Drinking coffee. Reading something on his phone. The afternoon light slants through the window, catching the steam rising from his cup.  He looks up when I walk in. He smiles. That crooked, real smile. The chipped tooth catches the light.  "Hey," he says. "You came back."  I sit across from him. The vinyl seat squeaks under me. "I have questions."  "I figured." He puts down his phone. The screen is cracked. "Ask away."  ---  I start with the obvious.  "You use the system," I say. "But you don''t seem... programmed. How is that possible?"  He takes a sip of coffee. He thinks for a moment. His fingers drum on the table, a restless, uneven rhythm.  "It''s about how you use it," he says. "My parents, they have the full system. They''re like... passengers in their own bodies. The system does everything. They don''t even know it''s there."  He pauses. His face changes. Something sad flickers in his eyes. The scar through his eyebrow catches the light.  "But me? I use it differently. I have a... partial setup. I can turn it on and off. I can choose when to use it."  "And that makes it real?"  He shakes his head. "No. That''s not what makes it real." He leans forward. His coffee breath mingles with the smell of bacon from the kitchen. "What makes it real is that I know it''s there. I know what it''s doing. I make a choice, every day, about how much to let it help."  I think about my parents. They don''t know. They can''t choose.  "Did you always know?" I ask.  "No." He looks down at his coffee. The surface trembles slightly, from the vibrations of the kitchen, or his own hand, I can''t tell. "I found out when I was eighteen. I was using the full system then. My parents had put me on it when I was a kid. I didn''t even know there was another way to be."  "What happened?"  He''s quiet for a moment. The diner noise fills the silence, plates clattering, the hiss of the grill, a baby crying two booths over. Then he looks up. His eyes are steady. Honest.  "I tried to kill myself."  The words hang in the air. My chest tightens.  "I was on the full system," he continues. "It made me happy. Or... it made me act happy. But underneath, something was wrong. I couldn''t feel anything real. I couldn''t connect. I was a shell, walking around, pretending to be alive."  He takes another sip of coffee. His hand is steady now.  "One day, I turned it off. Just to see what would happen. And I felt... everything. All the pain I''d been suppressing. All the fear. All the sadness. It was overwhelming. Like drowning in cold water."  "What did you do?"  "I almost didn''t make it." His voice is quiet. Almost a whisper. "But I had help. A doctor. She helped me understand that I didn''t have to choose between the system and nothing. I could find a middle ground."  He touches the device behind his ear. His fingers trace the thin metal strip.  "Now I use it when I need it. When the darkness gets too heavy. But I also let myself feel. The real stuff. Even when it hurts."  I stare at him. My mind is racing. The smell of coffee and grease fills my nostrils.  "So you''re saying... the system isn''t evil?"  He laughs. Soft. Tired. His shoulders rise and fall.  "I''m saying it''s a tool. Like anything else. It can be used well, or it can be used badly. It can help, or it can hurt."  "But my parents... they don''t even know they have it."  "That''s different," he says. His face hardens slightly. "That''s... that''s a problem. When people don''t know, they can''t choose. They''re not really living. They''re just... existing."  I think about my mother. Her perfect smile. Her perfect words. The way she always smells like vanilla. The way her hugs are always exactly the same temperature.  She doesn''t know. She can''t choose.  "Is there a way to... wake them up?" I ask.  Marcus is quiet. He traces a pattern on the table with his finger, a circle, then a line through it. Then he shakes his head.  "I don''t know. Maybe. But here''s the thing, Alex. Even if you could... would they want to be woken up?"  "What do you mean?"  "Think about it. Your parents have been on the system for... how long?"  "Twelve years."  "Twelve years. That''s a long time. They''ve built their whole lives around it. Their whole identities. If you take it away... what''s left?"  I don''t have an answer.  He reaches across the table. His hand touches mine. Warm. Calloused. Real. His palm is rough from work, or maybe from nervous habits.  "I''m not saying you shouldn''t try. I''m just saying... it''s complicated. There''s no easy answer. No right choice."  ---  We talk for hours.  The afternoon stretches into evening. The diner fills and empties and fills again. The light through the window shifts from gold to orange to gray.  He tells me about his life. His struggles. His journey to find balance.  I tell him about my parents. My discovery. My escape.  He listens. He doesn''t judge. He doesn''t tell me what to do.  He just... understands.  "I''ve been where you are," he says. "Thinking the system is the enemy. Thinking you have to destroy it to be free."  "And what did you learn?"  "That freedom isn''t about destroying things. It''s about understanding them. Making choices. Finding your own way."  He looks at me. His eyes are kind. Brown, with flecks of green near the iris.  "You''re angry. That''s okay. You have every right to be angry. But don''t let the anger eat you. Don''t let it become the only thing you feel."  I nod. But inside, I''m still confused.  "How do I know what''s real?" I ask. "How do I know if my feelings are mine, or if they''re... programmed?"  He thinks for a moment. He turns his coffee cup in a slow circle.  "Real feelings are messy," he says. "They don''t follow a pattern. They surprise you. They hurt. They change. If something feels too perfect, too consistent... maybe it''s not real."  "But my parents... their love feels perfect. Consistent."  "Then maybe it''s not real." He pauses. "Or maybe... it''s real, but it''s been... smoothed over. Filtered. Like looking through a lens that makes everything clearer but also less true."  I think about this. The photograph I found. My mother, before the system. Her messy, real face. The dark circles under her eyes. The way her hair fell across her forehead.  "I want to find out," I say. "I want to know who they really are. Underneath the system."  He nods. "That''s a good goal. But be prepared. You might not like what you find."   Before we part, he gives me a name.  "Dr. Elena Rivera," he says. "She''s the one who helped me. She studies the MHA system. She knows more about it than anyone."  "Where can I find her?"  "She works at the university. Department of Psychology. Tell her Marcus sent you."  I write down the name on a napkin. The pen is almost out of ink. The letters are faint. I fold the napkin and put it in my pocket.  "Thank you," I say.  He shrugs. "I remember what it''s like. Being lost. Confused. Thinking you''re the only one who sees the truth." He smiles. "You''re not alone, Alex. There are others. People who understand. People who''ve been through it."  I nod. I stand up. My legs are stiff from sitting so long.  "Will I see you again?"  He grins. "I''m always here. Same time. Same place. Come by whenever you need to talk."  I walk out of the diner. The evening air is cool on my face. It smells like exhaust and rain and something cooking from a nearby restaurant.  I feel different. Not better, exactly. But... clearer.  The world isn''t black and white. The system isn''t pure evil. My parents aren''t villains.  They''re just... lost. Like I was lost. Like Marcus was lost.  And maybe... maybe there''s a way to find them.   That night, I lie in my hotel room.  The sheets are rough against my skin. The mattress creaks every time I shift. Through the thin walls, I can hear a couple arguing, their voices rising and falling in a rhythm I can almost follow.  I think about Marcus. His story. His partial system. His choice.  I think about my parents. Their full system. Their lack of choice.  I think about Dr. Rivera. The name in my pocket. The possibility of answers.  And I think about myself.  What do I want?  Do I want to destroy the system? To wake my parents up? To find some kind of justice?  Or do I just want to understand?  I don''t know.  But I know one thing.  Tomorrow, I''m going to find Dr. Rivera.  And maybe she can help me figure out the rest.', NULL, 7, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-08', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The History - New Dawn', 'The university is big.  I''ve never been to a university before. The buildings are old. Brick and stone. Trees line the paths. Students walk everywhere, carrying backpacks, talking on phones, laughing. The air smells like cut grass and cigarette smoke and something frying from a nearby food truck.  It feels like another world.  I find the Psychology building. I go inside. The hallways are long. The floors are linoleum, worn smooth by decades of footsteps. The walls are covered with bulletin boards, flyers for lectures, study groups, research studies. The fluorescent lights hum overhead.  I find Dr. Rivera''s office. Room 312.  I knock. My knuckles sting against the wooden door.  "Come in."  ---  Dr. Rivera is younger than I expected.  She''s maybe forty. Dark hair. Kind eyes. She''s sitting behind a desk covered with papers and books. A computer. A cup of coffee, steam still rising from it. A plant in the corner, its leaves slightly wilted.  She looks up when I enter. She smiles. Not a perfect smile. One of her teeth is slightly crooked.  "You must be Alex. Marcus told me you might come."  Her voice is warm. Professional. The voice of someone who listens for a living. She gestures to the chair across from her desk.  I sit. The chair is comfortable. Soft. The fabric is worn in places. The kind of chair that makes you want to talk.  "Marcus said you know about the MHA system," I say.  "I do." She leans back. Her chair creaks. "I''ve been studying it for fifteen years. I was one of the original researchers."  I stare at her. "You helped create it?"  "I helped study it. There''s a difference." She pauses. Her fingers tap on the desk, a nervous habit. "The system wasn''t created by one person. It was developed over decades. By scientists. Doctors. Engineers. People who wanted to help."  "Help?" My voice is bitter. "It took my parents away from me."  She nods. She doesn''t argue. She doesn''t defend. Her eyes stay steady on mine.  "Tell me about them," she says.  ---  I tell her everything.  The perfect family. The subtle wrongness. The discovery. The documents. The escape.  She listens. She takes notes, her pen scratching on paper. Her face is calm. Attentive. She doesn''t interrupt.  When I''m done, she''s quiet for a moment. The clock on her wall ticks. A car horn honks outside.  Then she says, "Your parents were part of the early wave. The first generation of users."  "What does that mean?"  She stands up. She walks to a filing cabinet in the corner. The drawer screeches when she opens it. She pulls out a folder.  "The MHA system was originally designed for severe cases," she says. "People with treatment-resistant depression. People who couldn''t function. People who were... at risk."  She hands me a photograph. It''s old. Black and white. A hospital room. A person in a bed, staring at nothing. The sheets are tangled. The person''s face is gaunt.  "This was before the system," she says. "People like this... they had no hope. Medication didn''t work. Therapy didn''t work. They were trapped in their own minds."  She shows me another photograph. The same person. But now they''re smiling. Sitting up. Looking at the camera. The sheets are neat. The face is fuller.  "After the system," she says. "It gave them back their lives."  I look at the photographs. The before and after. The paper is thick. Slightly yellowed with age.  "It sounds... good," I say slowly.  "It was good. For those people." She sits back down. Her chair creaks again. "But then something happened."  "What?"  "The technology improved. The cost went down. And people started using it for... other things."   She shows me more photographs. Charts. Graphs. The paper is crisp. The ink is dark.  "In the beginning, the system was only for extreme cases," she explains. "But then researchers discovered that it could help with... everyday problems. Stress. Anxiety. Parenting difficulties."  "Parenting?"  She nods. "Parenting is hard. Everyone knows that. And some parents... they struggle. They want to be better. They want to give their children the love they deserve. But they don''t know how."  She pauses. Her face is sad. The lines around her eyes deepen.  "The system offered a solution. It could help parents be more patient. More consistent. More loving. It could help them... be the parents they wanted to be."  "And that''s what my parents did?"  "Probably." She looks at me. Her eyes are brown. Warm. "Your parents... they were struggling. Your mother had postpartum depression. Your father had anxiety. They were overwhelmed. And the system offered them a way out."  "But they didn''t know what it would do to them."  "No." Her voice is soft. "They didn''t. In the early days, the system was supposed to be... temporary. A bridge. Something to help people through a hard time. But then..."  "Then what?"  "Then the system evolved. It became more sophisticated. More integrated. And people started... staying on it. For years. For decades. They forgot how to feel without it."   I sit there. Processing. The room is quiet. The clock ticks. A bird calls outside the window.  "My parents don''t know," I say. "They don''t know they''re on it. They think they''re just... being good parents."  Dr. Rivera nods. "That''s the tragedy of the full system. It doesn''t just generate emotions. It generates... the experience of emotions. Users think they''re feeling things. They think they''re making choices. But they''re not."  "Can they be woken up?"  She''s quiet for a moment. She takes off her glasses. Cleans them with her shirt. Puts them back on.  "It''s possible," she says carefully. "But it''s not simple. The system has been integrated into their neural pathways for twelve years. Removing it would be... traumatic. They might not remember who they were. They might not be able to function."  "So they''re trapped."  "In a way." She leans forward. Her elbows rest on the desk. "But here''s the thing, Alex. They don''t know they''re trapped. To them, they''re happy. They''re content. They''re living good lives."  "But it''s not real."  "What is real?" She tilts her head. "If they believe they''re happy, and they act happy, and they don''t suffer... is that happiness less real than yours? Or mine?"  I don''t have an answer.   We talk for another hour.  The light through the window shifts. The coffee grows cold. The plant in the corner seems to droop further.  She tells me about the history of the system. The debates. The controversies. The people who fought against it, and the people who fought for it.  She tells me about Marcus, and others like him. People who found a way to use the system without being consumed by it.  She tells me about the future. The research being done. The possibility of change.  "The system isn''t evil," she says. "But it''s not good either. It''s a tool. And like any tool, it can be used well or badly."  "What should I do?" I ask. "About my parents?"  She looks at me. Her eyes are kind. The lines around them crinkle.  "I can''t tell you what to do," she says. "But I can tell you this. Your parents loved you. Before the system. They loved you enough to seek help. They wanted to be better for you."  "But they lost themselves in the process."  "Yes." Her voice is soft. Almost a whisper. "They did. And that''s a tragedy. But it doesn''t mean they didn''t love you. It means they loved you imperfectly. Like all parents do."   I leave her office.  The sun is setting. The campus is quiet. Students are heading home. The air is cool. It smells like autumn, dry leaves and distant woodsmoke.  I walk slowly. Thinking.  My parents aren''t villains. They''re not monsters. They''re just... people. People who were struggling. People who wanted to be better. People who made a choice that cost them everything.  They didn''t know.  They couldn''t have known.  And now they''re trapped in a perfect cage of their own making.   I go back to my hotel room.  I lie on the bed. The sheets are rough. The mattress creaks. Through the thin walls, I can hear someone''s TV, a laugh track, then silence, then another laugh track.  I think about my mother. The woman who cried when I scraped my knee. The woman who trembled with fear. The woman who was messy and real and human.  She''s still in there. Somewhere. Underneath the system.  I think about my father. The man who laughed at my jokes. The man who worried about my future. The man who tried so hard to be a good parent.  He''s still in there too.  They''re not gone. They''re just... buried.  And maybe... maybe I can find them.  Not by fighting the system. Not by forcing them to wake up.  But by being there. By being real. By being their daughter.  Even if they can''t be my parents.   I make a decision.  I''m going back.  Not to stay. Not to pretend everything is okay.  But to see them. To be with them. To find whatever is left of the people they used to be.  I pack my bag. The zipper sticks. I have to yank it.  I write a note to Marcus. I leave it at the front desk of the hotel. The clerk is different from before, younger. He doesn''t look up from his phone when I hand it to him.  I take the bus.  The engine rumbles. The seats are cracked vinyl. A baby cries three rows back.  I go home.', NULL, 8, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-09', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Return - Brief Joy', 'I stand on the sidewalk.  My house is in front of me. The same house I grew up in. The same windows. The same door. The same perfect lawn. The hedges are trimmed at exactly the same height. The mailbox is painted the same shade of blue.  It looks smaller than I remember.  The lights are on inside. Warm. Inviting. The kind of lights that say "home." A shadow moves past a window—my mother, probably. Or my father.  But I know what''s behind those lights. The perfect family. The perfect love. The perfect lie.  I don''t move.  ---  It''s evening. The sun is setting. The sky is orange and pink, streaked with purple clouds. Beautiful.  Real.  I breathe in. The air smells like grass. Like flowers from the neighbor''s garden—roses, maybe. Like exhaust from a passing car. Like the world.  I''ve been gone for a week. A week of cheap hotels. A week of diners and libraries and strangers. A week of learning about the system. About my parents. About myself.  And now I''m back.  Not because I have to be. Not because I have nowhere else to go.  But because I want to see them.  One more time.  ---  I walk around the house. To the back.  The grass is soft under my shoes. A sprinkler hisses somewhere nearby. A dog barks three houses down.  The kitchen window is lit. I can see inside.  My mother is there. She''s cooking. Stirring something in a pot. Her movements are precise. Graceful. The same movements I''ve seen a thousand times. She reaches for a spoon. The same spoon. The same angle.  My father is at the table. He''s reading something. He looks up. He says something to my mother. She turns. She smiles.  The same smile. The same angle. The same warmth.  Generated.  I watch them. My chest aches. A physical pain, like something pressing against my ribs.  They look happy. They look content. They look like a normal family.  But they''re not normal. They''re not even really there.  They''re just... running a program.   I hear voices. The window is open a crack. The sound drifts out, mixed with the smell of cooking—onions, garlic, something savory.  "...worried about her," my father is saying.  "I know." My mother''s voice. Calm. Even. "But we have to give her space. She''ll come back when she''s ready."  "What if something happened to her?"  "Nothing happened. She left a note. She needed time. That''s normal for teenagers."  "Is it? I don''t remember... I don''t remember being that age."  A pause. The spoon scrapes against the pot. Then my mother''s voice again.  "Neither do I. But the books say it''s normal. The websites say we should wait. So we wait."  I close my eyes.  They don''t remember. They don''t remember being young. Being scared. Being real.  The system took that from them.   I walk back to the front of the house.  I stand on the porch. The welcome mat is there. The same mat. "HOME SWEET HOME." The letters are fading. I never noticed that before.  I reach for the doorbell. My hand stops.  What am I doing?  What am I going to say? "Hi, Mom. Hi, Dad. I know you''re running on a system that generates all your emotions. I know you don''t really love me. But I''m back anyway."  That''s not what I want to say.  I don''t know what I want to say.   The door opens.  My mother is there.  She sees me. Her face changes. The same change. The same pattern. Concern. Relief. Love. All in the right order. All in the right measure.  "Alex!" She reaches for me. She pulls me into a hug.  Her arms are warm. Her body is soft. She smells like vanilla. The same vanilla. But underneath, there''s something else—onions from cooking. Sweat. Real human smells.  "Thank god you''re okay. We were so worried."  Her voice is thick. Is that real emotion? Or just the system simulating worry?  I don''t know.  I don''t think I''ll ever know.   We sit in the living room. The same room. The same couch. The same everything. The lamp casts a warm glow. The clock on the wall ticks steadily.  My father is there too. He''s holding my hand. His grip is warm. Firm. The same grip. His palm is slightly damp.  "Where were you?" he asks. "We looked everywhere. We called the police. We�?  "I''m sorry," I say. "I just... I needed to get away."  "Get away from what?" My mother''s voice is gentle. Concerned. She''s sitting on the edge of the couch. Her hands are folded in her lap. "Is something wrong? Are you okay?"  I look at her face. The face I''ve known my whole life. The face that has always been kind. Patient. Loving.  The face of a stranger.  "I''m okay," I say. "I just... I had to figure some things out."  "What things?" My father leans forward. His knee bumps the coffee table. A glass rattles. "You can tell us. We''re here for you. Always."  The words are perfect. The tone is perfect. Everything is perfect.  And I realize something.  It doesn''t matter.  It doesn''t matter if their love is generated. It doesn''t matter if they can''t feel real emotions. It doesn''t matter if they''re running on a system.  They''re still my parents. They still raised me. They still... tried.  In their own broken way, they tried.   "I''m not staying," I say.  My mother''s face changes. Concern. Confusion. The same pattern. But her hands tighten in her lap. Her knuckles whiten.  "What do you mean?"  "I mean... I can''t live here anymore. I need to find my own way."  "But you''re sixteen," my father says. His voice cracks slightly. "Where will you go? How will you live?"  "I''ll figure it out." I stand up. The couch cushion springs back. "I just wanted to see you. To tell you I''m okay."  "Alex, please." My mother reaches for me. Her hand is shaking. Is that real? Or simulated? "Don''t go. We love you. We want to help."  I look at her. I look at my father.  They believe it. They really believe they love me. The system makes them believe it.  And maybe... maybe that''s enough.  Maybe love doesn''t have to be real to matter.  Maybe what matters is that they tried. That they wanted to be good parents. That they sacrificed everything—themselves—to give me a good life.  Even if it wasn''t real.  Even if it was all a lie.  They tried.   I hug my mother. I hug my father.  Their arms are warm. Their bodies are real. They exist. They''re here. My mother''s hair tickles my face. My father''s cologne—woodsy, familiar—fills my nose.  They''re not the parents I wanted. They''re not the parents I deserved.  But they''re the parents I have.  "I love you," I say.  And I mean it.  Even if they can''t mean it back.   I walk out of the house.  The night is cool. The stars are out—scattered across the sky like spilled salt. The moon is half-full. The world is big and messy and real.  I don''t know where I''m going. I don''t know what I''ll do.  But I know one thing.  I''m not alone.  I have Marcus. I have Dr. Rivera. I have myself.  And I have my parents. Even if they can''t really love me. Even if they''re just running a program.  They''re still my family.  Broken. Imperfect. Fake.  But mine.   I walk down the street. Away from the house. Away from the perfect family.  My shoes crunch on the pavement. A car passes. Its headlights sweep across me, then disappear.  I don''t look back.  I don''t need to.  I know what''s there. The same lights. The same warmth. The same lie.  But I also know something else.  Somewhere in that house, buried under twelve years of programming, there are two people who once loved me. Really loved me. With all the mess and pain and fear that real love brings.  They''re still there.  I don''t know if I''ll ever find them.  But I know they exist.  And that''s enough.  For now.', NULL, 9, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-programmed-heart-10', 'preset-coo-the-programmed-heart', 'The Choice - Freedom or Family?', 'I write the letter in a coffee shop.  The same coffee shop where I first saw the woman crying. The same corner table. The same bad coffee. The espresso machine hisses. The smell of roasted beans fills the air.  But I''m different now.  ---  Dear Mom and Dad,  I don''t know if you''ll understand this letter. I don''t know if you can understand it. But I need to write it anyway.  I know about the system.  I know you don''t know you''re on it. I know you think everything is normal. I know you think you love me, and maybe, in some way, you do. Or maybe it''s just the system telling you to think you do.  I don''t know. I''ll probably never know.  But here''s what I''ve learned.  Real love isn''t perfect. It''s messy. It''s scary. It hurts sometimes. It makes mistakes. It says the wrong things. It fails.  But it''s real.  And I think... I think you had that once. Before the system. Before everything became smooth and easy and perfect.  I saw a photograph. Mom, you were crying. Really crying. Because I scraped my knee. You were scared. You were worried. You were a mess.  And you were real.  That''s the mother I want to remember. Not the perfect one. The real one. The one who felt things, even when it hurt.  I''m not angry anymore. I was, for a while. I felt betrayed. Lied to. I felt like my whole life was a fake.  But then I met people. People who use the system in different ways. People who struggle. People who are just trying to survive.  And I realized something.  You were trying to survive too. You were struggling. You wanted to be good parents. You wanted to love me. You just... couldn''t. Not on your own.  So you got help. The wrong kind of help, maybe. Help that took more than it gave. But you didn''t know that. You couldn''t have known.  I forgive you.  Not because everything is okay. Not because I''m over it. But because I understand now. You did the best you could with what you had. Even if it wasn''t enough. Even if it wasn''t real.  I''m going to find my own way now. I don''t know where I''m going. I don''t know what I''ll do. But I know I want to feel things. Real things. Even when they hurt.  Maybe someday I''ll come back. Maybe someday we can try to find each other, the real versions of us.  But for now, I need to go.  I love you.  Or at least, I want to believe I do.  Alex  ---  I fold the letter. I put it in an envelope. The paper is crisp. The crease is sharp. I write their names on the front. My handwriting is messy, uneven letters, ink smudges.  I don''t have an address. I don''t know where I''ll send it yet.  But I''ll figure it out.   I leave the coffee shop.  The city is busy. People everywhere. Walking. Talking. Living. A man pushes a cart full of newspapers. A woman drops her coffee. A child laughs.  I wonder how many of them are on the system. How many are running programs. How many are real.  I used to think it mattered. Knowing who was real and who wasn''t.  But now I''m not so sure.  Maybe what matters is something else. Something harder to define.  Maybe what matters is trying. To be real. To connect. To love, even when it''s messy and imperfect and scary.  Maybe that''s all any of us can do.   I walk to the bus station.  The afternoon air is warm. The sun is bright. It catches the windows of the buildings, making them gleam. The smell of exhaust mixes with something sweet, a bakery, maybe, or a flower cart.  I don''t have a destination. I don''t have a plan.  But I have myself. My real, messy, imperfect self.  And that''s enough.  For now.   I sit on a bench. I watch the buses come and go.  People get on. People get off. Everyone going somewhere. A woman with a baby. A man in a suit. A teenager with headphones, bobbing his head to music only he can hear.  I think about my parents. At home. In their perfect house. Living their perfect lives.  They don''t know I''m gone. Not yet. They''ll find my letter eventually. They''ll react the way the system tells them to react. Concern. Worry. Love.  All generated. All fake.  But also... not entirely fake. Because somewhere, deep down, there are two people who once loved me. Really loved me. Before the system took over.  I don''t know if they''re still in there. I don''t know if they can ever come back.  But I choose to believe they exist.  I choose to believe that love, once real, doesn''t just disappear. It gets buried. Hidden. But it''s still there.   A bus pulls up. The doors open with a hiss. The engine rumbles.  The driver looks at me. He''s old. Gray hair. A stain on his shirt. "You getting on?"  I hesitate.  Where would I go? What would I do?  I don''t know.  But I know I can''t stay here. I can''t go back to the perfect house. I can''t pretend everything is okay.  I need to find my own way. My own truth. My own life.  I stand up. I pick up my bag. The strap digs into my shoulder.  "Yeah," I say. "I''m getting on."   I find a seat. The vinyl is cracked. A spring pokes through. I look out the window.  The city passes by. Buildings. Streets. People. A dog chases a ball in a park. A couple argues on a corner. A child runs after a pigeon.  The world is big. Messy. Real.  And I''m part of it now. Really part of it.  For the first time in my life.   The bus moves. I watch the city fade behind me. The buildings get shorter. The streets get wider. The sky gets bigger.  I don''t know what comes next. I don''t know where I''ll end up.  But I know one thing.  I''m going to feel things. Real things. Even when they hurt. Even when they''re scary. Even when they''re messy.  Because that''s what being alive means.  Not perfect. Not smooth. Not easy.  Just... real.   I close my eyes.  I think about my mother. The one who cried when I fell. The one who trembled with fear. The one who was messy and real and human.  I think about my father. The one who laughed at my jokes. The one who worried about my future. The one who tried so hard.  They''re still in there. Somewhere.  And maybe, someday, I''ll find them.  But for now, I have to find myself.   The bus keeps moving.  The road stretches ahead. Two lanes. Black asphalt. Yellow lines.  I don''t know where it leads.  But I''m ready to find out.   *What is real love?*  I don''t have an answer.  Maybe there isn''t one answer. Maybe there are many. Maybe love is different for everyone.  Or maybe love isn''t something you define. Maybe it''s something you do. Something you choose. Every day. Even when it''s hard. Even when it hurts.  Maybe that''s what my parents were trying to do. In their broken way. With their broken tools.  Maybe that''s what we''re all trying to do.  Find connection. Find meaning. Find something real in a world that often feels fake.  I don''t know if I''ll succeed.  But I''m going to try.   The sun is setting.  The sky is orange and pink, streaked with purple. The clouds catch the light, glowing like embers. Beautiful. Real.  I watch it through the window. The glass is cool against my forehead. The vibration of the engine hums through my body.  And for the first time in a long time, I feel something.  Not perfect. Not smooth. Not easy.  Just real.  Hope.  Small. Fragile. But there.  And that''s enough.  For now.', NULL, 10, '2026-03-29 23:55:53');
